wiki.content:
This is a great rendition of a Sonny Rollins written tune, which I became familiar with on an amazing juke box which had that rarity of jazz singles.  The juke was at the entrance of the legendary now defunct Slugs Jazz club in New York City.  The cut was with that incredible Quintet that featured Trane with Miles!  How I love it!  The apex of early 60's driving post bop jazz at its big league best.
 Arthur Huppert ("arturohup") 
 Merion Station, PA

track.name: Airegin
comments: One of my favorites is human nature , by michael Jackson

Airegin (Nigeria) - Some people suppose that the title was inspired by the political development in Nigeria (Africa in general was changing due to an atmosphere of political emancipation generated by African intellectuals after World War II) at that time. Not only Sonny Rollins was fascinated by that but many Black American Jazz musicians who had to suffer from racism in the States.

1956 - the second recording of Airegin - Miles Davis Quintet - featuring John Coltrane and Red Garland (first recording summer 1954 with Horace Silver - the band started without piano accompaniment until the first solo chorus when Horace Silver came in)
